# Unit Testing

## 🚫 NEVER Write Tests Unless Explicitly Asked

> **This is the most important rule in this document. It overrides any instinct to be helpful by adding tests.**

**Do NOT write, add, modify, or suggest unit tests at any point unless the user's message explicitly and directly requests it.**

This means:
- ❌ Do not add tests when building new features or components
- ❌ Do not add tests when fixing bugs
- ❌ Do not update existing tests when changing code they cover
- ❌ Do not mention tests as a next step, suggestion, or recommendation
- ❌ Do not ask if the user wants tests added

✅ **Only write tests when the request clearly calls for it**, such as:
- "Write a test for..."
- "Add test coverage for..."
- "Can you test this component?"

If there is any ambiguity about whether the user wants tests, **do not write them**.

---

## Stack

| Tool | Role |
|---|---|
| **Vitest v4** | Test runner and assertion library |
| **@testing-library/react** | Component rendering and queries |
| **@testing-library/user-event** | Simulating real user interactions |
| **@testing-library/jest-dom** | Extra matchers (`toBeInTheDocument`, etc.) |
| **jsdom** | Simulated browser environment (no real browser) |

## Commands


npm run test:run      # Single run with coverage (use in CI or to check results)
npm test              # Watch mode — re-runs on file save
npm run test:coverage # Coverage only
```

## File Structure

```
src/__tests__/
├── setup.js                          # Loads jest-dom matchers globally
├── utils/
│   └── businessHelpers.test.js       # Pure utility function tests
├── components/
│   ├── StepBreadcrumb.test.jsx
│   └── ThemeToggle.test.jsx
└── pages/
    └── SignUpPage.test.jsx
```

Test files must match `**/*.{test,spec}.{js,jsx}` to be picked up by Vitest.

CSS and SCSS imports are automatically ignored (`css: false` in `vite.config.js`).

## Required Wrappers

### Components that use ThemeContext
```jsx
import { ThemeProvider } from '../../contexts/ThemeContext';

render(
  <ThemeProvider>
    <MyComponent />
  </ThemeProvider>
);
```

### Pages that use React Router
```jsx
import { MemoryRouter } from 'react-router-dom';

render(
  <MemoryRouter>
    <ThemeProvider>
      <MyPage />
    </ThemeProvider>
  </MemoryRouter>
);
```

### Pre-seeding the theme via localStorage
```js
localStorage.setItem('insureco-theme', 'g100'); // set before render
```
Always call `localStorage.clear()` in `beforeEach` to avoid test bleed.

## Mocking Carbon Icons

Carbon icons are SVG components that add no test value. Always mock them:

```js
vi.mock('@carbon/icons-react', () => ({
  Checkmark: ({ className }) => <span data-testid="icon-checkmark" className={className} />,
  ArrowRight: () => <span />,
  Asleep: () => <span data-testid="icon-moon" />,
  Light: () => <span data-testid="icon-sun" />,
}));
```

Only add `data-testid` when the test needs to assert the icon's presence.

## Mocking useNavigate

```js
const mockNavigate = vi.hoisted(() => vi.fn());
vi.mock('react-router-dom', async (importOriginal) => {
  const actual = await importOriginal();
  return { ...actual, useNavigate: () => mockNavigate };
});
```

## Mocking Browser APIs Not in jsdom

```js
// window.scrollTo is not implemented in jsdom
Object.defineProperty(window, 'scrollTo', { value: vi.fn(), writable: true });
```

## User Interaction Pattern

```jsx
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event';

it('submits the form', async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup();
  render(<MyForm />);
  await user.type(screen.getByLabelText(/email/i), 'test@example.com');
  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i }));
  expect(mockNavigate).toHaveBeenCalledWith('/success');
});
```

Always `await` userEvent calls — they are async.

## What to Test

- **Utils**: Test all branches and edge cases of pure functions
- **Components**: Test rendering, props, user interaction, and state changes
- **Pages**: Test multi-step flows, field validation, navigation, and conditional rendering

## Coverage

Run `npm run test:run` to see coverage. The report shows per-file statement/branch/function/line coverage. Current overall coverage is low (~10%) because most pages and business components are not yet tested.
